FFI and native calls may block in ways the runtime cannot observe. Options include:

- require annotation for blocking calls (Java's `@Blocking`, Tokio's `spawn_blocking` convention);
- run FFI calls on a dedicated blocking pool with elastic sizing;
- detach the worker's scheduling token before entering the call (Go's M can become detached when blocked in a syscall);
- pin virtual threads during native calls (Loom's pinning behaviour);
- forbid certain calls in async contexts (most async runtimes warn or panic).

The choice between these is one of the most consequential parts of designing an async / virtual-thread runtime: getting it wrong leaks blocking into the scheduler and starves unrelated tasks.
